==================================================
SFTP CONNECTION ISSUE - COMPLETE GUIDE
(Issue, Root Cause, Fixes, and F5 Clarification)
==================================================

SECTION 1: WHAT HAPPENED
-------------------------
- OS patching upgraded OpenSSH from 8.x to 9.x on the SFTP server
  (Oracle Linux 9.8).
- Right after this, external SFTP/AD connections through the F5 load
  balancer stopped working.
- A manual/direct test on the SFTP server showed the SSH "key
  exchange" step succeeding, which made the server look fine.
- LWSD/PBIS logs showed the real error: "no matching host key type"
- These failing connection logs pointed to the F5 LB's IP address as
  the source (explained in Section 5 - this is normal, see below).


SECTION 2: THE SIMPLE EXPLANATION
-----------------------------------
Before any username, password, or AD check happens, the SFTP server
must first prove its identity to whatever is connecting. It does
this using a specific "signature style."

- The server used to prove its identity using an old style called
  "ssh-rsa."
- The OpenSSH upgrade turned that old style OFF by default. The
  server now only offers newer styles.
- The manual test used modern software, so it understood the new
  styles fine and connected.
- The external systems making the real AD/SFTP connections are
  running older software that ONLY understands the old style.
- The moment they connect, the server offers its ID in a format
  they don't recognize, and the connection dies right there -
  before login even starts.

Where the issue lives: on the SFTP server itself, at the very first
handshake step, before authentication. It is NOT F5, NOT Active
Directory, and NOT PBIS - all of those sit downstream and never
even get reached.


SECTION 3: ROOT CAUSE (technical)
------------------------------------
- Starting with OpenSSH 8.8, the old "ssh-rsa" signing method
  (SHA-1 based) was disabled by default because SHA-1 is considered
  cryptographically broken. This carried forward into 9.x.
- The RSA host key itself does NOT need to be replaced. OpenSSH has
  been able to sign with that same RSA key using a stronger method
  (SHA-256/512, called "rsa-sha2") since 2016. Modern clients use
  this automatically without any special setup.
- Old clients that only understand the literal "ssh-rsa" name fail
  immediately during negotiation - before any authentication logic
  runs.
- PBIS/LWSD is not the cause. It's simply where the failed attempt
  happens to surface in this environment's logs, since PBIS handles
  AD authentication, which never gets reached.


SECTION 4: IMMEDIATE FIX (already applied - restores connectivity)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Check current host keys:
   ls -la /etc/ssh/ssh_host_*key*

2. Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config and add:
   HostKeyAlgorithms +ssh-rsa

3. If key-based (not just password) login is used, also add:
   PubkeyAcceptedAlgorithms +ssh-rsa

4. Restart SSH:
   systemctl restart sshd

5. Confirm it applied:
   sshd -T | grep -i hostkeyalgorithms
   (ssh-rsa should now be listed)

6. Retest the external connection while watching:
   journalctl -u sshd -f
   The "no matching host key type" error should be gone.

NOTE: This fix works, but it is a temporary bridge. It re-enables an
older, weaker signing method that was disabled for security reasons.


SECTION 5: IS F5 INVOLVED? (short answer: no fix needed on F5)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
- F5 in this setup is just forwarding traffic through - it is not
  part of the SSH conversation itself.
- Proof: the failing connections are reaching sshd on the Linux box
  and dying at the negotiation step. That can only happen if F5
  already let the traffic through successfully. If F5 itself were
  the problem, the attempt would never even reach sshd to fail this
  way.

WHY THE LOGS SHOW F5'S IP INSTEAD OF THE REAL CLIENT'S IP:
  F5 is doing something called SNAT (Secure Network Address
  Translation). Think of F5 as a front desk that lets every visitor
  in, then walks them over to the SFTP server's office. The
  server's log records "front desk" as the visitor - not the actual
  outside person - because technically the front desk is who walked
  through last. But the front desk didn't speak on the visitor's
  behalf. Whatever that visitor actually said (the SSH negotiation,
  "I only speak ssh-rsa") is untouched and still theirs - F5 just
  carried it in.

  SNAT is normal and intentional. It means F5's IP will show up for
  EVERY external connection - the ones that work and the ones that
  fail alike. On its own, this is NOT evidence that F5 is the
  outdated component.

ONE THING WORTH CONFIRMING WITH THE F5 TEAM (to be 100% sure):
  Ask: "Is this virtual server doing plain TCP forwarding, or does
  it have an SSH Proxy / inspection profile attached?"
  - Plain TCP forwarding (the common setup) -> confirms it's still
    the external client's own old software failing. Fix stays only
    on the Linux box.
  - SSH Proxy / inspection enabled -> then F5 itself is acting as
    the SSH client toward your server, and F5's own SSH stack would
    need to support the newer algorithm too. Worth ruling out, but
    this is a less common setup.

SIDE EFFECT WORTH KNOWING:
  Because of SNAT, sshd's logs only ever show F5's IP, not the real
  external client's IP. This means you can no longer tell which
  specific external partner is failing just by reading the Linux
  server's logs. To get the real client IP, the F5 team would need
  to add their own logging rule (an iRule) on the BIG-IP side -
  plain SSH/SFTP traffic has no automatic way (like a web request
  header) to carry the original IP forward.


SECTION 6: PERMANENT FIX PLAN
---------------------------------
The real permanent fix is not another server setting - it's getting
every external connection off the literal "ssh-rsa" algorithm
entirely, so the "+ssh-rsa" line becomes unnecessary and can
eventually be removed.

STEP 1 - Find out exactly what's still using the old method:
  journalctl -u sshd | grep "no matching host key type"
  (See the SNAT caveat in Section 5 - this may show F5's IP rather
  than the real partner's IP.)
  For deeper detail on client software/version, temporarily set
  LogLevel DEBUG in sshd_config, restart, reproduce the failure,
  then check the "remote software version" log line - revert the
  log level afterward.

STEP 2 - Upgrade those clients (the actual fix):
  rsa-sha2 support has been standard for close to a decade now.
  Most non-ancient software already supports it and will use it
  automatically once upgraded - no special configuration is needed
  on the partner's end. Once every external source supports it,
  delete "+ssh-rsa" from sshd_config entirely.

STEP 3 - Make sure a modern host key exists too:
  ls -la /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key
  If missing, generate one:
  ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key -N ''
  Then add this line in sshd_config alongside the existing RSA line:
  HostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key
  This doesn't force anything - modern clients pick the stronger
  key type up automatically; nothing changes for clients that can't
  use it.

STEP 4 - For anything that genuinely cannot be upgraded:
  Do not leave "+ssh-rsa" applied globally. Scope it to just that
  one legacy system so nothing else is weakened. Example (place in
  its own file under /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/ so it's easy to find
  and remove later):

     Match Address <legacy-partner-ip-or-subnet>
         HostKeyAlgorithms +ssh-rsa
         PubkeyAcceptedAlgorithms +ssh-rsa

  IMPORTANT CAVEAT: this only works if sshd can actually see the
  real partner's IP address. If F5's SNAT sits in front of the
  connection (see Section 5), sshd will only ever see F5's IP, and
  this Match block will not correctly distinguish between partners.
  In that case, get the real client IP from the F5 team first (via
  their iRule/local logging), or discuss an alternative with them,
  such as a dedicated SNAT address per legacy partner if feasible.

  Always validate config before restarting:
  sshd -t
  (catches typos before they lock you out)

STEP 5 - Set a retirement date:
  Put a reminder to recheck the logs in about 90 days. Once no real
  ssh-rsa negotiations show up anymore, remove the exception for
  good.


SECTION 7: QUICK REFERENCE - WHERE THE ISSUE LIVES
------------------------------------------------------
  Issue location:   SFTP server (Oracle Linux 9.8), sshd, at the
                     very first handshake step - before
                     authentication.

  NOT the cause:     F5 load balancer (just forwarding/SNAT),
                     Active Directory, PBIS/LWSD (never reached).

  Confirm only if:   F5 has an SSH Proxy/inspection feature enabled
                     - ask the F5 team to confirm which type of
                     virtual server this is.

